Acer, AU Optronics, China Steel, Compal: Taiwan Stocks Preview

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-07-14T00:47:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-14/acer-au-optronics-china-steel-compal-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
may have unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of last close in Taipei  The Taiex Index fell 2.95 points, or less than 0.1 percent,
to 8,488.06.  Flat Panel companies.  AU Optronics Corp. (2409)  (2409 TT) had its
share-price estimate cut 30 percent to NT$14.80 and rating
maintained at “sell” at Samsung Securities Co.  Chimei Innolux
Corp. (3481)  (3481 TT) was lowered to “sell” from “hold” at Samsung
Securities. The brokerage said in a report rising inventories,
and slow demand should restrain prices and hurt earnings. AU
added 0.3 percent to NT$17.35. Chimei decreased 0.6 percent to
NT$16.90.  Personal-computer related companies: Global PC shipments
rose less than forecast amid a sluggish economy and consumer
preference for smartphones and Apple Inc.’s iPad tablet,
according to market-research firms IDC and Gartner Inc.  Acer
Inc. (2353)  (2353 TT) dropped 0.8 percent to NT$41.55.  Asustek Computer
Inc. (2357)  (2357 TT) lost 0.9 percent to NT$271.50.  China Steel Corp. (2002)  (2002 TT): Taiwan’s largest producer of
the metal will cut domestic prices by an average 1.7 percent for
September contracts because of slow demand from customers,
including automakers. The stock advanced 0.9 percent to
NT$35.05.  Compal Electronics Inc. (2324)  (2324 TT): The world’s second-
largest contract maker of notebooks agreed to buy a Mexico
factory from Toshiba Corp. as it expands production of
televisions amid a slowing market for computers. The stock fell
1.5 percent to NT$33.50.  MediaTek Inc. (2454)  (2454 TT): The island’s largest chip
designer’s board approved plans to buy back 8 million shares, or
0.73 percent of those outstanding, the Hsinchu, Taiwan-based
company said in an exchange filing yesterday. The stock slid 5.7
percent to NT$247.  Taiwan  Semiconductor Manufacturing Co. (2330 TT): The
world’s largest contract chipmaker was cut to “neutral” from
“overweight” at JPMorgan Chase & Co. by equity analyst Rick
Hsu. The nine-month share-price estimate is NT$77. The stock
gained 2.7 percent to NT$72.20.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 